To calculate the distance between San Francisco and London, we can use the Haversine formula, which is an equation important in geodesy (the science of designing and constructing Earth-based structures).
The Haversine formula computes the distance between two points on the Earth's surface using the Vincenty parameter (a^2, b^2, c^2, and d^2), which are related to the ellipsoidal geometry of the Earth. The formula takes into account the flattening of the Earth's surface, the eccentricity of the Earth's surface, and the distance between the two points.
Here's the MATLAB code to calculate the distance between San Francisco and London using the Haversine formula:
```
% Define the coordinates of San Francisco and London
lat1 = deg2rad(37.7749);
lon1 = deg2rad(-122.4194);
lat2 = deg2rad(51.5074);
lon2 = deg2rad(-0.1278);
% Convert the latitude and longitude to radians
lat1 = rad2deg(lat1);
lon1 = rad2deg(lon1);
lat2 = rad2deg(lat2);
lon2 = rad2deg(lon2);
% Compute the Haversine distance
d = 6371 * asin(sqrt(cos(lat1)*cos(lat2) + sin(lat1)*sin(lat2)*cos(lon1 - lon2)));
% Convert the distance to meters
d = 6371 * d;
% Display the distance
fprintf('The distance between San Francisco and London is %.2f meters.\n', d);
